## Hazard conventions

Safety information appears throughout, following ANSI Z535.6. The first three
levels concern injury to people and carry the safety alert symbol. The last two
do not: one concerns damage to property, the other is guidance on working
safely, and neither means a person can be hurt.

The examples below are all drawn from a kitchen. That is deliberate — they
demonstrate the form without resembling anything that belongs in a real manual,
so there is no way to leave one in by mistake.

### What goes in a safety message

A hazard message states three things, and is not finished until it states all
three:

1. **The hazard** — what the dangerous thing is.
2. **The consequence** — what happens to the reader if they meet it.
3. **How to avoid it** — what to do instead.

The avoidance goes *inside* the panel, with the hazard it belongs to. Splitting
it into a separate block further down means a reader who acts on the alert alone
has been told they might be hurt and nothing else, and means the two halves
drift apart the next time someone edits the procedure.

### The five levels

**DANGER** — hazard which, if not avoided, **will** result in death or serious
injury. Reserved for the extreme case, where meeting the hazard is not a matter
of chance.

:::{danger}
The dough hook of a running mixer will crush and sever fingers. Switch the mixer
off and wait for the hook to come to a complete stop before reaching into the
bowl.
:::

**WARNING** — hazard which, if not avoided, **could** result in death or serious
injury.

:::{warning}
Frying oil left unattended can ignite and spread fire across the kitchen,
causing severe burns. Stay with the pan whenever the heat is on. If the oil
catches, turn off the heat and smother the pan with a lid — never move it and
never use water.
:::

**CAUTION** — hazard which, if not avoided, could result in **minor or moderate
injury**.

:::{caution}
Trays coming out of a hot oven will burn exposed skin. Use dry oven gloves; a
damp cloth conducts heat straight through to your hand.
:::

**NOTICE** — practices not related to personal injury. Damage to equipment, to
the work, or to data.

:::{notice}
Opening the oven during the first twenty minutes will collapse the cake. Wait
until the top has set before checking on it.
:::

**SAFETY INSTRUCTIONS** — safe work practices, grouped at the start of a section
rather than attached to any one hazard. Not an alert in either direction.

:::{safety-instructions}
Tie back long hair and roll back loose sleeves before working near the mixer.
Keep a lid within arm's reach whenever a pan is on the heat. Know where the fire
blanket is before you need it.
:::

**NOTE** — useful information that is not safety-related. Not a signal word, and
not a safety message.

:::{note}
Butter taken straight from the fridge creams more slowly than butter left to
come up to room temperature.
:::

### Choosing between them

The line between CAUTION and NOTICE is the one that matters: if a person can be
hurt it is CAUTION or higher, and if only property is at risk it is NOTICE. A
ruined cake is a NOTICE; the tray it came out on is a CAUTION.

Use them sparingly. A manual where every paragraph is a warning is a manual
where none of them are read.
